.chap(PPL's Extension Features,extension)
.see extension,language,|data definition, operator definition|

The language facilities presented so far in this
manual do not distinguish PPL from a number
of other interactive, conversational programming
languages that were available long before PPL
was implemented.  The most notable of these
are <<APL> (after which much of PPL's conversational
mechanics were patterned) and <<JOSS> and its derivatives.
Indeed, APL has a large set of
elegant array operations and other features which
are not present in PPL.

What sets PPL apart from these is that it is
an !<extensible language>; that is,
it contains facilities for !<extending> the language
in several directions.
In fact, we have already presented one type of extension,
namely the ability to enter user-defined functions,
thereby extending the set of functions subsequently
available to the user.  However, the ability to define
functions is present in almost every programming language;
thus, PPL is not an extensible language for this reason alone.

The two areas of extension we shall now cover are (1)
the definition of new unary and binary operators, and (2)
the definition, construction, and manipulation of
user-defined data types.

.sec(User-Defined Operators,opdef)
.see definition,operator,operator definition

As has already been mentioned in passing,
the execution of unary and binary operators is considered
to be a special case of system function calling;
thus, the expression 3A+B1  is evaluated as 3ADD(A,B)1.
This is done through a predefined association between
the operator '+' and the built-in function ~ADD~.
However, the user is allowed to change this association
and to define new operators.

An operator in PPL is a sequence of
one to four characters
taken from the following set:

.examp
.x operator character
.x character,used for operator
\! # $ % & + - * / ^ _ . : ; , < = > \ [ ] ( ) @
.end

.see function,associating operator with,|UNARY, BINARY|
New operators are defined and associated with built-in or user-defined
functions of the programmer's choice by use of the functions
~@/<UNARY,operator definition/>~ and ~@/<BINARY,operator definition/>~.  The call

.examp
\UNARY(!<o>,!<f>,!<p>)
.end

establishes a new unary operator !<o> (where !<o> is a ~@@<STRING,to describe operator>~
of one to four characters chosen from the list above) and
associates it with the function !<f>, which must be
a function taking a single argument.  !<p>, if given, specifies
the operator's precedence, which is an integer in the range
1 to 32767.  We shall postpone discussion of precedence
until later.

For example, the statement

.examp
\UNARY("\/", SQRT)
.end

establishes a new unary operator '\/' which, when applied to
some operand, returns its square root using the built-in
function {fn(SQRT,a)}.  For example:

.examp
\\/3.17
1.780449
\FOR I_1:8 DO PRINT(\/I, " ")
1. 1.414214 1.732051 2. 2.236068 2.44949 2.645751 2.828427
\\/(3^2 + 4^2)
5.
.end

Similarly, the built-in function

.examp
\BINARY(!<o>,!<f>,!<p>,!<a>)
.end

establishes a new binary operator !<o> and associates it with
the function !<f> (built-in or user-defined), which must
take two arguments.  The precedence !<p> and associativity !<a>
will be discussed later and may be omitted in the call.

In the following example, we shall
create a function ~<<REMAIN>~, which takes
two ~REAL~ arguments
and returns the remainder resulting from dividing
the first by the second.  We shall then associate
this function with the binary operator '\';
this is done by calling the built-in function ~BINARY~.
Having done this, we may then use the '\' operator
freely within expressions for
computing the remainder.

.examp
\$REMAIN(A,B)
   [1]\REMAIN_A-B*INT(A/B)
   [2]\$

\REMAIN(5.0,3.0)
2.
\BINARY("\",REMAIN)
\5.0\3.0
2.
\(34.2+547.1)\37.0
26.3
.end

Redefinition of existing operators
.x redefinition of operator
.x operator redefinition
may be done in exactly the same manner.
A word of caution is in order.
When writing a function designed to take over the meaning of
a commonly-used operator (such as '+'),
the user must take care not to use that operator
within the definition of the function.
Any such use of the operator will result in a &/<recursive call/by/operator redefinition>
of the function;  this is not usually what is
intended!
Also note that since the built-in operations
are still accessible by name (the ~ADD~ function, for example),
it is possible to restore the original meaning
.x restoring original meaning of operator
of an operator that has been redefined.
For example:

.examp
\BINARY("+",ADD)
.end

As a trivial illustration of such redefinition, we might
change the division operator so as to call the built-in function
~<<IDIV>~ rather than ~<<DIV>~ (recall that in the division of an ~INT~ by another
~INT~, ~IDIV~ throws away the remainder and always returns an ~INT~, whereas
~DIV~ returns a ~REAL~ if the remainder is nonzero).

.examp
\7/3
2.333333
\BINARY("/",IDIV)
\7/3
2
.end

A more elaborate situation could arise were we to write a program
in which all integer arithmetic needed to be done, say, modulo 256.
Addition modulo 256 might be implemented as follows:

.examp
\$<<ADD.MOD.256>(A,B); S
   [1]\S_ADD(A,B)
   [2]\IF A==INT & B==INT THEN WHILE S>255 DO S_SUB(S,256)
   [3]\RETURN S
   [4]\$

\BINARY("+",ADD.MOD.256)
\23+45
68
\185+97
26
\42+95+142+88+196
51
\42.+95.+142.+88.+196.
563.
.end

The operator '==' used in ~ADD.MOD.256~ is the '&<instance/operator> of'
operator;  its value is ~TRUE~ if its left operand is of the type
specified as its right operand, otherwise ~FALSE~.
Hence the expression 3A==INT1 is ~TRUE~ if ~A~ is of type ~INT~
and ~FALSE~ otherwise.

Subtraction, multiplication, and division modulo 256 could be
accomplished in much the same manner.  Notice that we were
careful to preserve the existing behavior of the '+' operator
in cases where one or both operands are not ~INT~s.

The following operators have special meaning in
the syntax of PPL and cannot be redefined:

.examp
.x reserved operator
.x operator,reserved
\(   )   [   ]   ,   ;   ;;   :   ::   =>
.end

However, it !<is> legal to define new operators
that have the above-mentioned symbols embedded
within them.

An @<operator definition,erasing> may be erased by calling
~@/<UNARY,NULL/argument to>~ or ~@/<BINARY,NULL/argument to>~ with a second argument which is ~NULL~
or "" (a ~STRING~ of length zero).  For example, the
binary meaning of the operator '\' (defined above)
could be erased by:

.examp
\BINARY("\",NULL)
.end

.sec(Operator Precedence,precedence)
.x precedence

Every operator in PPL (whether built-in or user-defined)
has an attribute called its !<precedence>, as we first saw
in {"Section!" desk}.  In the absence of parentheses,
the relative precedence of operators in an expression
determines the order in which those operations are performed.
An expression such as 32*3^4+51 is evaluated
as 3(2*(3^4))+51 because '^' is of
greater precedence than '*', which in turn is of greater precedence
than '+'.

The precedence of an operator is given by an integer in the
range 1 to 32767, and may optionally be specified as the third
argument in calls to the functions ~@/<UNARY,precedence/specification in>~ and ~@/<BINARY,precedence/specification in>~.
If this argument is omitted, a new unary operator will be
assigned @<precedence,default> equal to that of the built-in unary
operators ('+' and '-'), whereas a new binary operator will be
assigned a precedence lower than all existing operators except
assignment ('_').  However, if the precedence is omitted
while !<redefining> an !<existing> operator, the precedence
will be inherited from the old definition.

The following table gives the precedence of all of PPL's
built-in operators:

.begin nofill group indent 8 tabs 15
.x precedence,table
.xx plus operator,precedence,of
.xx minus operator,precedence,of
.xx arithmetic operator,precedence,of
.xx power operator,precedence,of
.xx multiplication operator,precedence,of
.xx division operator,precedence,of
.xx addition operator,precedence,of
.xx subtraction operator,precedence,of
.xx instance operator,precedence,of
.xx comparison operator,precedence,of
.xx equal operator,precedence,of
.xx less than operator,precedence,of
.xx less than or equal operator,precedence,of
.xx greater than operator,precedence,of
.xx greater than or equal operator,precedence,of
.xx not equal operator,precedence,of
.xx logical operator,precedence,of
.xx and operator,precedence,of
.xx or operator,precedence,of
.xx assignment operator,precedence,of
.xx noncopy assignment operator,precedence,of
.xx goto operator,precedence,of

100\+  -  (unary)
90\^
80\*  /
70\+  -  (binary)
60\==
50\=  <  <=  >  >=  #
40\&
30\!
20\_  __
10\-->
.end

(The operator '__' will be presented in {"Section!" copshr}
and '-->' in {"Section!" syntax}.)
The default precedence for new unary operators is 100, and for
new binary operators 25.  (These numbers are the values of
built-in variables called ~<<DEF.UNARY.PREC>~ and ~<<DEF.BINARY.PREC>~,
which may be assigned new values by the user who desires to
change the defaults).

Binary operators have another attribute called !<associativity>,
which determines the order of evaluation of expressions
containing operators of !<equal> precedence.  Most common
operators are !<left associative>, meaning that the order
of evaluation of expressions such as 3A+B+C+D1 is
left to right, i.e. 3((A+B)+C)+D1.  However, in some
cases, such as multiple assignment, it is desirable for the
.xx assignment operator,associativity,of
operations to be done from right to left;  e.g.
3A_B_C_01 should be evaluated as 3A_(B_(C_0))1.
Such operators we describe as !<right associative>.
'^' is also a right associative operator since the
.xx power operator,associativity,of
conventional algebraic interpretation of expressions such as

.begin nofill indent 8 turn on "^[]"

ab^[c^d]  is  a(b^[(c^d)])  rather than  ((a^b)^c)^d.
.end

The &/<associativity/specification in/BINARY> of an operator is specified by supplying
the ~@@<STRING,as associativity specification in BINARY> "LEFT"~ or ~"RIGHT"~ as the fourth argument to ~BINARY~ (PPL looks
at only the first character).  Where this argument is not supplied,
the &<default/associativity> for !<new> binary operators is left associativity
and for !<existing> operators the associativity of the previous
definition.
(The default associativity actually used is the value of the
built-in variable ~<<DEF.ASSOC>~, which is initially the string ~"LEFT"~.)

An obscure case arises if a unary operator and a binary operator
.x precedence conflict,resolution of
with the same precedence, or two binary operators with
the same precedence but opposite associativity,  are used in an expression.  For example,
if we define

.examp
\BINARY("@",MANGLE,70,"RIGHT")
.end

then the order of evaluation of 3A@B+C1 is unclear because
binary '+' also has a precedence of 70 but is left associative.  By convention, the associativity
of the rightmost operator is used to resolve the conflict.
3A@B+C1 is evaluated as 3(A@B)+C1 in this case, because
'+' is a left associative operator.  Were '+' right associative,
the expression would instead be evaluated as 3A@(B+C)1,
regardless of the associativity of '~@~'.

.sec(Built-In Functions Dealing with Operators,builtinopdef)

PPL provides several built-in functions for obtaining information
about defined operators.*<At present these functions are
unimplemented in the PDP-11 version.>
These are as follows:

.begin indent 0,20 tabs 21
{fn(UNARY.DEF,o)}\Returns as a ~STRING~ the name of the function
associated with the unary operator !<o>, which is also given
as a ~STRING~.  Hence 3UNARY.DEF("-")1 returns 3"MINUS"1.
If !<o> is not defined as a unary operator, the result returned
is "" (a ~STRING~ of length zero).

{fn(BINARY.DEF,o)}\Returns as a ~STRING~ the name of the function
associated with the binary operator !<o>.  Hence
3BINARY.DEF("-")1 returns 3"SUB"1.  If !<o> is
not defined as a binary operator, "" is returned.

{fn(UNARY.PREC,o)}\Returns the unary precedence (an ~INT~eger)
of the operator !<o>, or zero if !<o> is not defined as
a unary operator.

{fn(BINARY.PREC,o)}\Returns the binary precedence of the operator !<o>,
or zero if !<o> is not defined as a binary operator.

{fn(ASSOCIATIVITY,o)}\Returns the associativity of the binary operator
!<o> as the ~STRING "LEFT"~ or ~"RIGHT"~, or "" if !<o> is not defined
as a binary operator.

~<<OPERATORS>~\(A parameterless procedure) Returns a list of all
defined operators as a ~<<TUPLE>~ of ~STRING~s (~TUPLE~s will be
presented in {"Section!" builtinddef}).
.end

The functions ~UNARY.PREC~ and ~BINARY.PREC~ are convenient to use
when defining new operators.  For example, to define a new
unary operator '*' with precedence just below that of the
binary operator '+', we might say:

.examp
\UNARY("*", STAR, BINARY.PREC("+")-3)
.end

This avoids the necessity of consulting the precedence table
given in the previous section.


.sec(RENUMBER and Iversonian Precedence,iversonian)

When the operator definition facility is used heavily, the
situation may arise in which it is no longer possible
to interpolate between the precedence of existing operators
.xx precedence,interpolation,in scale of
when assigning the precedence for a new operator.
To alleviate this condition, the library function {fn(RENUMBER,n)}
may be used.  This function changes the precedence of all
defined operators in such a way that subsets of equal-precedence
operators are separated in precedence by !<n>
(which must be a positive integer).

Previous versions of PPL did not include the operator precedence
scheme described in the preceding section, but rather
employed a much simpler convention called !<Iversonian precedence>.
.x Iversonian precedence
.x precedence,Iversonian
In this scheme, all operators are of the same precedence and
right-associative, as is the case in the language <<APL>.
(This precedence scheme is named after %%<K.E./Iverson>,
the designer of APL.)

In order to provide compatibility with older PPL programs or
to accomodate user preference for Iversonian precedence,
there exists a parameterless procedure ~<<IVERSONIAN>~ which, when called,
causes PPL to revert to Iversonian precedence conventions.
Specifically, ~IVERSONIAN~ changes all existing operators to have the
same precedence and right associativity, and changes the values
of the variables ~DEF.UNARY.PREC~, ~DEF.BINARY.PREC~, and ~DEF.ASSOC~
correspondingly so that further definitions also conform to Iversonian
precedence.

Complete @@<compatibility,with old PPL programs> with programs written prior to PPL-10 version 52
may be obtained by executing the following statements !<before>
reading in such programs:*<The order is important because operator precedence and associativity are applied at the time a function is defined, not when it is executed.>

.examp
\IVERSONIAN
\BINARY("/",<<IDIV>)
.end

Neither ~RENUMBER~ or ~IVERSONIAN~ is defined as part of the basic
system, but must be obtained from the system library, which may
be different for the various installations at which PPL is supported.
This information should be maintained in the local "news" file.

.sec(Data Definitions,datadef)
.see definition,data,data definition
.x data definition

Of the six data types already presented,
five (~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~, ~BOOL~, and ~CHAR~)
are !<atomic>, meaning that they are the basic
forms predefined within PPL and are indecomposable.
A number of built-in operations may be performed on these types;
most of these operations have already been presented.

Being an extensible language, PPL contains
the mechanisms required for defining and
manipulating new types of data.  Once the user has
defined a data type, he may write functions for
manipulating instances of that type, and he may
associate these functions with symbolic operators
of his own choosing
in the manner just presented.
The result is that
complicated programs involving
lists, trees, and other such structures
may be written simply.  Through the use of
data and operator definitions, PPL may be extended to
such a degree that simple expressions become quite
powerful in their actions.

.ssec(Structure Definitions,strdef)
.x data definition,structure

In PPL we may define three different
classes of @<data type,user-defined>s.  First, we may have
structures.  A !<structure> is a datum consisting
of any number of named parts (possibly of different types).
We will make use of the following example to
explain the use of %<structure/definition>s:

.examp
\$<<COMPLEX> = [RP:REAL, IP:REAL]
.end

This is read: "A ~COMPLEX~ is defined to be a structure
containing an ~RP~ of type ~REAL~ and an ~IP~ of
type ~REAL~" (where ~RP~ is being used to
stand for 'real part' and ~IP~ for 'imaginary part').
Issuing this definition causes the following
actions to be taken:

First, a !<constructor> function ~COMPLEX~
.see function,constructor,constructor function
.xx structure,constructor function,for
is created by PPL.  This is a function which
takes as many arguments as there are
elements in the data definition (i.e. two for ~COMPLEX~),
and creates a datum of type ~COMPLEX~.  For example,

.examp
\X_COMPLEX(3.7, 59.0)
.end

assigns to ~X~ a value obtained by constructing
a ~COMPLEX~ whose ~RP~ is 3.7 and whose ~IP~
is 59.0.  The types of the arguments must
agree with the types of the corresponding components
in the data definition.

Second, each identifier to the left of a colon
.see function,selector,selector
.x structure,selector for
.x selector
is defined to be a !<selector>.  A selector
is a function that operates on a constructed
datum and selects one of its components.
In the definition of ~COMPLEX~ above,
~RP~ and ~IP~ are defined as selectors.
An example of the <<selection> operation is as follows:

.examp
\R_RP(X)
\R
3.7
\13+IP(X)
72.
.end

The selection operation may alternatively
be denoted in !<subscript notation> by placing
.xx selector,subscript notation,for
the selector name within @@<square brackets,enclosing selector>
immediately following the value from which
the selection is being made, thus:

.examp
\X[RP]
3.7
\13+X[IP]
72.
.end

Third and finally, the name of the
data definition (~COMPLEX~) is also defined
as a !<predicate>.
A &/<predicate/for/structure> is an identifier which is the
name of the given data type.
This name may then be used in other
data definitions and as arguments to certain
functions and operations that take data types
as arguments.
One of these, which we glanced at in {"Section!" opdef},
is the '==' operator.  It takes as its
.x instance operator
left operand a value, which it checks against the
right operand which must be a predicate.
If the value is an instance of the predicate, the
'==' operator returns the value ~TRUE~; if not, the result
is ~FALSE~.  For example, having constructed
a ~COMPLEX~ and assigned it to the variable ~X~,
we may execute the following statements:

.examp
\X==COMPLEX
TRUE
\3.427==COMPLEX
FALSE
.end

At this point we should note that
predicates also exist for the five atomic data types.
These predicates, as one might expect, are named
~@/<INT,predicate/>~, ~@/<REAL,predicate/>~, ~@/<DBL,predicate/>~,
~@/<BOOL,predicate/>~, and ~@/<CHAR,predicate/>~.
The following example will illustrate their use:

.examp
\3==INT
TRUE
\4.529==INT
FALSE
\V_93+45.2/6*3.5
\V==REAL
TRUE
.end

.ssec(Sequence Definitions,seqdef)

The second type of data definition we may
make is a !<sequence> definition.
.x data definition,sequence
A sequence is a datum consisting of any number
of homogeneous, numbered parts.
The indexing is done by some contiguous subset
of the integers.

As an example of a %<sequence/definition>, we
will define:

.examp
\$<<ROW> = [1: ] REAL
.end

which is read:  "Define a ~ROW~ to be a sequence
of ~REAL~s, indexed by integers starting
at 1 and extending to an indefinite upper limit".

As is the case for structures, issuing
a sequence definition causes a &/<constructor function/for/sequence>
to be created by PPL.  The constructor function
~ROW~ will take any number of arguments of type ~REAL~
and will construct a ~ROW~ out of them.
For example,

.examp
\X_ROW(3.56, -28.59/2, 3*55.21/4)
.end

assigns to ~X~ a ~ROW~ consisting of three elements
which are the values of the three arguments.

Given a datum of type ~ROW~, we may select
any one of its elements by means of !<indexed selection>
.x selection
.see index,subscript
.xx sequence,selector,for
or !<subscripting>.  When the value of ~X~ was constructed,
the first element of the ~ROW~ was associated
with the index 1, the second with the index 2, and the
third with the index 3.  We select a component
of ~X~ by placing the desired index
(which must be an expression of type ~INT~) in square brackets
after the name ~X~, thus:

.examp
\X[1]
3.56
\I_3
\Q_X[I-1]
\Q
-14.295
\(Q+X[I])/2
13.55625
.end

Note that the indices start at the number
specified on the left side of the colon
in the sequence definition.  Thus, if we had defined
~ROW~ as:

.examp
\$ROW = [-10: ] REAL
.end

then the three elements of ~X~ would be ~X[-10]~, ~X[-9]~,
and ~X[-8]~.  Attempts to select nonexistent elements
of a sequence will result in an execution error.

Making a sequence definition also causes
a &/<predicate/for/sequence> to be created, as is the case for 
a structure definition.  We may test for
occurrences of sequences in exactly the same way as for
structures:

.examp
\X==ROW
TRUE
\X==COMPLEX
FALSE
.end

We may also make sequence definitions with
&/<fixed upper bound/for/sequence>s;  for example:

.examp
\$<<ROW4> = [1:4] INT
.end

defines ~ROW4~ to be a sequence of four components
of type ~INT~, numbered 1, 2, 3, and 4.

.ssec(Alternate Definitions,altdef)
.x data definition,alternate
.x definition,alternate
.x alternate definition

The third form of data definition we may make
is an !<alternate> definition, which
defines a new @@<predicate,defined by alternate definition> to be the !<union>
of any number of other predicates.
.see union of predicates,alternate definition
For example:

.examp
\$<<ARITH> = INT ! REAL ! DBL
.end

defines an ~ARITH~ to be either an ~INT~, a ~REAL~,
or a ~DBL~.  The names on the right side of the definition
may be built-in predicates (e.g. ~INT~), user-defined
predicates (e.g. ~COMPLEX~),
or predicates defined in other alternate definitions.

Predicates defined in alternate definitions
are useful in a variety of ways.  The first is in
explicit type checking:

.examp
\3.276*54 == ARITH
TRUE
\X_ROW(3.56, -28.59/2, 3*55.21/4)
\X==ARITH
FALSE
\X[3]/X[2] == ARITH
TRUE
.end

Thus, in the case of this definition of ~ARITH~,
the expression

.examp
\X==ARITH
.end

is a more compact representation of the expression

.examp
\X==INT ! X==REAL ! X==DBL
.end


However, alternate types are much more powerful
than this.  Consider the following definition:

.examp
\$<<VECTOR> = [1: ] ARITH
.end

Given such a definition, it is possible to construct
~VECTOR~s consisting of any set of components
which are defined as being of type ~ARITH~
(i.e. ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~).
The following example illustrates the behavior of
this kind of construction:

.examp
\X_VECTOR(3, 7.9, 1.54/7)
\X[1]
3
.apart group
\X[1]==INT
TRUE
\X[1]==REAL
FALSE
\X[1]==ARITH
TRUE
.apart group
\X[3]==REAL
TRUE
\X[3]==ARITH
TRUE
.end

As may be seen above, the arguments to a constructor
defined in this way need not all be of the same type, so long
as each one's type is an alternative of the predicate ~ARITH~.

.sec(Built-In Data Definitions,builtinddef)

There exist five %<built-in/predicate>s
with the following properties:

.begin indent 4,20 tabs 21
~<<ATOMIC>~\The union of all atoms
(~INT~, ~REAL~, ~DBL~, ~BOOL~, and ~CHAR~).

~<<STRUCTURE>~\The union of all structures.

~<<SEQUENCE>~\The union of all fixed sequences
(i.e. those with upper bound specifications).

~<<V.SEQUENCE>~\The union of all variadic sequences
(i.e. those with no upper bound specifications).

~<<GENERAL>~\The union of all data types in the entire
system (both built-in and user-defined).
.end

There also exists the following
built-in data definition:

.examp
\$@/<TUPLE,data definition/> = [1: ] GENERAL
.end

that is, a ~TUPLE~ is a sequence of any length
containing any objects as its components.
The usual data operations may be
performed using this definition;
for example:

.examp
\X_TUPLE(3,'Q,TUPLE(4.1,"ABCDE"))
.end

However, a more concise syntax is available
for constructing ~TUPLE~s.  A ~TUPLE~
is indicated by a list of zero or more
values enclosed in @@<square brackets,enclosing TUPLE>.
For example:

.examp
.tabs 9,40
\X_[3,'Q,[4.1,"ABCDE"]]\7a TUPLE of length 3
3\Y_[TRUE]\7a TUPLE of length 1
3\Z_[]\7a TUPLE of length 0
.end

~TUPLE~s are very convenient in many applications,
since they effectively allow the manipulation of structures
of arbitrary length and arbitrary type components.
However, this is achieved at some expense in
internal storage and execution &/<efficiency/of/data definition>.  Thus, when
this flexibility is not needed, it is preferable
to utilize structures and sequences with fixed element type.
For example, given the following definitions of ~ROW~ and
~VECTOR~ (made in {"Section!" datadef})

.examp
\$<<ROW> = [1: ] REAL

\$<<VECTOR> = [1: ] ARITH

\$<<ARITH> = INT ! REAL ! DBL
.end

one should note that a ~VECTOR~ takes over twice as much
space to store as a ~ROW~ of the same length,
even if in a particular case the components are of identical type (e.g. ~REAL~).
This is because, in the case of the ~VECTOR~, PPL must
take into account the possibility that some of the elements
might be ~INT~s or ~DBL~s, which take different
amounts of storage from ~REAL~s.
This uncertainty does not arise for the ~ROW~ because its
elements may only be ~REAL~s.

.sec(Printing User-Defined Values,printinguser)
.xx user-defined data,printout,of

When PPL is requested to print out the
value of a user-defined datum, it does so in
the following form:

.examp
\X_VECTOR(3, 7.9, 1.54/7)
\X
[3,7.9,.22]
\COMPLEX(5.7, -32.4)
[RP:5.7,IP:-32.4]
.end

In this representation, the square brackets
delimit the extent of the datum in question.
This is done because user-defined structures
may be nested.  For example, a two-dimensional
array might be defined, constructed, and displayed as follows:

.examp
\$<<ARRAY> = [1: ] <<VECTOR>

\A_ARRAY(X,VECTOR(3,2,1))
\A
[[3,7.9,.22],[3,2,1]]
\Q_1
\A[Q+1]
[3,2,1]
.end

.sec(More on Selection,selection)

Selection is a much more general operation
than the examples so far have shown.  First, a @/<selection expression,assignment/to>
may appear on the left side of an assignment
statement as well as on the right.
Such an operation causes the value of the right-hand
expression to be assigned as the selected component
of the given left-hand value (of course, this is legal
only if the right-hand expression is of the correct type).
A few examples will illustrate this behavior.

.examp
\X
[3,7.9,.22]
\X[2]_88.54E-27
\X
[3,8.854E-26,.22]
\X[2]
8.854E-26
.apart group
\A
[[3,7.9,.22],[3,2,1]]
\A[1]_A[2]
\A
[[3,2,1],[3,2,1]]
.end

Second, we may perform !<multiple selection>
.x multiple selection
.x selection,multiple
on compound structures whose elements are in turn
compound structures themselves.  The following
example illustrates two possible notations for
doing this in the case of user-defined sequences:

.examp
.tabs 9,40
\V1_VECTOR(11,12,13)
\V2_VECTOR(21,22,23)
\X_ARRAY(V1,V2,VECTOR(31,32,33))
\X
[[11,12,13],[21,22,23],[31,32,33]]
.apart group
\(X[1])[3]\7Select the third element of X[1]3
13
\X[1][3]\7Exactly equivalent to above3
13
\X[3][2]
32
\X[3,2]\7A more compact notation3
32
.end

For compound data types consisting of
structures, we have even more possibilities.
Let us define a ~<<NUM>~ as either an ~<<ARITH>~ (that is,
a ~REAL~, ~INT~, or ~DBL~) or a ~<<COMPLEX>~.
Then we shall define a ~<<NUMSEQ>~
as an arbitrary sequence of these types.

.examp
\$NUM = ARITH ! COMPLEX

\$NUMSEQ = [1: ] NUM

\X_NUMSEQ(3.42,COMPLEX(8.1,-33.0),-5)
.apart group
\X
[3.42,[RP:8.1,IP:-33.],-5]
\X[2][IP]
-33.
\X[2,IP]
-33.
.apart group
\RP(X[2])
8.1
\X[2,RP]_23.7
\X
[3.42,[RP:23.7,IP:-33.],-5]
.end

For convenience in writing routines that operate on
many different types of data, it is possible to
perform indexed (numeric) selection on structures
.xx structure,numeric selection,on
as well as sequences, with the lower bound assumed to be one.
For example, given the structure definition

.examp
\$COMPLEX = [RP:REAL, IP:REAL]
.end

then, if ~X~ is assigned a value of type ~COMPLEX~,
its components ~X[RP]~ and ~X[IP]~ may equivalently
be accessed as ~X[1]~ and ~X[2]~.

It should be noted at this point that
a ~@/<STRING,data definition/>~ is actually a compound data structure,
for which a data definition is predeclared in PPL.
This definition is:

.examp
\$STRING = [1: ] @@<CHAR,component of STRING>
.end

Thus, it is possible to access individual
characters of a ~STRING~ by selection.

.examp
\"STRING CONSTANT"[6]
G
\X_"STRING"
\X[4]_'U
\X
STRUNG
\X==STRING
TRUE
\X[4]==STRING
FALSE
\X[4]==CHAR
TRUE
.end

Note that a ~STRING~ is an exception to
.xx STRING,printout,of
PPL's usual printing convention.  Since a ~STRING~
is a compound datum, it would normally
be printed thus:

.examp
\"ABCDEFGH"
[A,B,C,D,E,F,G,H]
.end

However, PPL treats a ~STRING~ as a special
case and omits the compound structure notation.
Among other things,
this permits the common use of ~STRING~s for printing
out messages to the user.

.sec(Built-In Functions for User-Defined Data,builtinuser)

PPL contains a number of built-in functions
for manipulating user-defined data.  In some cases,
these functions could be written as user-defined
functions at considerable expense in space or time,
but have been built in to make them more efficient.

.begin indent 0,16 tabs 17
{fn(LENGTH,a)}\where !<a> is any value, returns the
number of components in !<a>
as an ~INT~.  If !<a> is atomic, {fn(LENGTH,a)}
is defined to be one.

{fn(L.BOUND,a)}\where !<a> may be a sequence or structure,
returns its lower bound as an ~INT~.
For a sequence, this is the number given on the left
side of the colon in the data definition; for
a structure, it is always one.

{fn(TYPE,a)}\Returns the data type of the argument !<a>
as a ~STRING~.
For example, if ~X~ is of type ~COMPLEX~, then the
value of ~TYPE(X)~ is the ~STRING "COMPLEX"~.

{fn(MAKE,t,n,e)}\Constructs a variadic sequence of
type !<t> containing !<n> elements, each of whose
initial values is !<e>.  Thus, !<t> must be the name
of a variadic sequence (i.e. one with no upper bound
specification) and !<e> be a value that may legally
be a component of instances of type !<t>.
Note that !<n> may be any arbitrary ~INT~-valued
expression, thus allowing the length of the
sequence to be determined at execution time.

{fn(CONCAT,a,b)}\where !<a> and !<b> are variadic sequences
of the same type, constructs a new variadic sequence
consisting of the concatenation of !<a> and !<b>,
with !<a> on the left and !<b> on the right.
Thus, ~CONCAT("PDP","-10")~ is ~"PDP-10"~,
and it is always true that

.begin nofill indent 19 select 3
LENGTH(CONCAT(!<a>,!<b>)) = LENGTH(!<a>)+LENGTH(!<b>)
.end; once preface 0 continue
Note (this is a common error) that it is !<not>
legal to ~CONCAT~ a ~STRING~ and a ~CHAR~, for
example, because a ~CHAR~ is not itself a sequence;
rather, a ~STRING~ is a sequence of ~CHAR~s.
There is a distinct difference in PPL between
a ~CHAR~ and a ~STRING~ containing one character.
.end

.sec(Sample Application:  Formula Manipulation,formula)
.x formula manipulation

As a demonstration of the power of the
operator and data definition facilities
presented so far, we
shall now give an example of formula
manipulation in PPL.
This should help tie together many of the features
explained in previous sections of the manual,
and shows how, through judicious choice of a few simple
data and operator definitions, we may create
a program with considerable power and elegance.

The first thing we shall do is devise a set of
data definitions to describe the data (formulas)
that we are going to manipulate.
There are two kinds of formulas that we may define,
namely unary formulas and binary formulas.
The following are %<unary/formula>s:

.begin nofill tabs 9 select 3

\-A     +(B-3)     -((A*B)/(-(C-D)))
.end

whereas these are %<binary/formula>s:

.begin nofill tabs 9 select 3

\X+3     (-Y)/(A+(B*C))     B*(C-D)
.end

Note that we distinguish the class of formula by
whether its principal operator is unary or binary.

Thus, a unary formula is a structure consisting of a unary
operator and a single operand which may in turn be
any kind of formula.  Similarly, a binary formula is
a structure consisting of a left operand, a binary operator,
and a right operand;  each operand may in turn be a formula.
Below are some abbreviations we shall use in defining
these structures to PPL (note that these are not
PPL statements but rather notes to ourselves).

.begin nofill tabs 9,17

\~FORM~\means Formula,
\~BF~\means Binary Formula,
\~UF~\means Unary Formula,
\~LO~\means Left Operand,
\~RO~\means Right Operand, and
\~OP~\means Operator.
.end

The required definitions are made to PPL as follows:

.examp
\$<<FORM> = <<UF> ! <<BF> ! <<ATOM>

\$UF = [OP:CHAR, RO:FORM]

\$BF = [LO:FORM, OP:CHAR, RO:FORM]

\$ATOM = STRING ! CHAR ! REAL ! INT ! DBL
.end

Note that these data definitions are !<mutually recursive>;
.xx data definition,recursion,in
that is, a ~FORM~ is defined as any of three other
data types, two of which (~UF~ and ~BF~) may contain
~FORM~s.  Note also that, in the definition of ~FORM~,
we referred to data types that had not yet been defined.
This is permitted in PPL because data definitions
are static and are not acted upon until it is necessary
to use them for actual data operations (e.g. construction
or selection).

Having made these definitions, we are now
in a position to construct formulas.
We shall use ~CHAR~acters to represent operators,
and ~CHAR~s or ~STRING~s to represent variable names.
Constants of type ~INT~, ~REAL~, or ~DBL~ will also
be permitted.  So, for example, we could create
the formulas 3X+31 and 3-(X*(X+3))1 with the following
PPL statements:

.examp
\F_BF('X, '+, 3)
\G_UF('-, BF('X, '*, F))
\F; G
[LO:X,OP:+,RO:3]
[OP:-,RO:[LO:X,OP:*,RO:[LO:X,OP:+,RO:3]]]
.end

Although the results are correct so far,
there are two difficulties that are immediately apparent,
namely the formulas are awkward to type in
and the output is hard to read.  Before proceeding
further with our formula manipulation example, we
should attempt to rectify these conditions.

We may use PPL's operator definition facility
to good advantage here by redefining all the
operators used in our formulas (namely the binary
operators '+', '-', '*', '/', and the unary operators
'+' and '-') so that they construct appropriate
.x formula,construction using operators
.x operator definition
formulas when they are used.  For example, we
want the PPL expression

.examp
\'X+3
.end

to generate a binary formula in the same manner
as the statement

.examp
\BF('X,'+,3)
.end

so as to make typing formulas more natural
for the user.  This may be done by
defining formula operation functions
(one for each operator), then associating them
with the desired operators.

.examp
.tabs 9,35
\$<<FADD>(A,B)\7%<formula/addition>3
   [1]\FADD_BF(A,'+,B)
   [2]\$

.apart group
\$<<FSUB>(A,B)\7%<formula/subtraction>3
   [1]\FSUB_BF(A,'-,B)
   [2]\$

.apart group
\$<<FMUL>(A,B)\7%<formula/multiplication>3
   [1]\FMUL_BF(A,'*,B)
   [2]\$

.apart group
\$<<FDIV>(A,B)\7%<formula/division>3
   [1]\FDIV_BF(A,'/,B)
   [2]\$

.apart group
\$<<FPLUS>(A)\7unary plus for formulas3
   [1]\FPLUS_UF('+,A)
   [2]\$

.apart group
\$<<FMINUS>(A)\7%<formula/negation>3
   [1]\FMINUS_UF('-,A)
   [2]\$

.apart group
\<<BINARY>("+",FADD); BINARY("-",FSUB)
\BINARY("*",FMUL); BINARY("/",FDIV)
\<<UNARY>("+",FPLUS); UNARY("-",FMINUS)
.end

Having done this, we may now type in formulas
in a much more natural way; for example:

.examp
\'X+3
[LO:X,OP:+,RO:3]
\G_ -('X*F)
\G
[OP:-,RO:[LO:X,OP:*,RO:[LO:X,OP:+,RO:3]]]
.end

To avoid having to keep typing in the single quotes
to enter the characters representing common variables
such as ~A~ and ~X~, we may define variables of
the same names to have these characters as values:

.examp
\A_'A; B_'B; C_'C; X_'X; Y_'Y; Z_'Z
\A/B*(X+Y-Z)
[LO:[LO:A,OP:/,RO:B],OP:*,RO:[LO:[LO:X,OP:+,RO:Y],OP:-,RO:Z]]
.end

Now that we have made formulas easy to type in, we
would like to be able to read them more readily
when they are printed out.  To do this, we shall write
a simple function called ~PF~, which will
print out a formula in more standard form.
.xx formula,printout,of
The required definition is as follows:

.examp
\$<<PRINT.FORM>(F)
   [1]\IF F==ATOM THEN PRINT(F); RETURN
   [2]\PRINT("("); IF F==BF THEN PRINT.FORM(F[LO])
   [3]\PRINT(F[OP]); PRINT.FORM(F[RO]); PRINT(")")
   [4]\$

.apart group
\$<<PF>(F)
   [1]\PRINT.FORM(F); ""
   [2]\$
.end

The ~PF~ function simply invokes the ~PRINT.FORM~
function (which does not advance the line), then
advances the line by directly printing a null ~STRING~.
{fn(PRINT.FORM,f)} prints any datum !<f> of type ~FORM~;
i.e. legal arguments may be ~UF~s, ~BF~s, ~INT~s,
~REAL~s, ~DBL~s, ~CHAR~s, and ~STRING~s.
This function prints a structure (~UF~ or ~BF~)
by recursively calling itself for each of its components.
For example:

.examp
\PF(F)
(X+3)
\PF(G)
(-(X*(X+3)))
\PF(A/B*(X+Y-Z))
((A/B)*((X+Y)-Z))
.end

The result is clearly more readable.  To save a little
more typing on the part of the user, we may associate
a unary operator with the ~PF~ function, as follows:

.examp
\UNARY("@", PF, SUB(BINARY.PREC("+"),5))
\@G
(-(X*(X+3)))
.end

Now that we have a reasonable mechanism for
input and output of formulas, we want to do something
interesting with them.
We shall define a function
that performs differentiation on any formula
.see differentiation,DERIV
containing the operators '+', '-', '*', and '/'.
The ~DERIV~ function takes two arguments; the first
is the formula to be differentiated, and the second
is the variable of differentiation 
(represented by a ~CHAR~).
The ~DERIV~ function computes derivatives by
recursive applications of the following well-known
identities:

.begin nofill group tabs 9,28

\(d/dx) constant =\0
\(d/dx) x =\1
\(d/dx)(a+b) =\da/dx + db/dx
\(d/dx)(a-b) =\da/dx - db/dx
\(d/dx)(a*b) =\a*db/dx + b*da/dx
\(d/dx)(a/b) =\(b*da/dx - a*db/dx) / b{super(2)}
.end

These rules may be coded into PPL statements
quite directly.  Note that ~DERIV~ is going
to have to call itself recursively in many places.
To reduce the amount of typing we must do while
defining the function, we shall first associate
a binary operator with the function so that we may
use it to make recursive calls. (Recall the
warning in {"Section!" opdef} about inadvertently making
&/<recursive call/by/operator redefinition>s through operator definition; in this
case we want to do exactly that).
PPL allows the user to associate an operator
with a function that has not yet been defined;
it is only when we actually try to use the
operator to perform its respective operation that
the function must exist.

.examp
\BINARY("\", DERIV, ADD(BINARY.PREC("*"),5))

.apart group
\$<<DERIV>(F,X)
   [1]\IF F==ATOM THEN IF F=X THEN RETURN 1 ELSE RETURN 0
   [2]\IF F==UF THEN RETURN UF(F[OP],F[RO]\X)
   [3]\IF NOT(F==BF) THEN "IMPROPER ARG TO DERIV"; RETURN
   [4]\IF F[OP]='+ THEN RETURN F[LO]\X + F[RO]\X
   [5]\IF F[OP]='- THEN RETURN F[LO]\X - F[RO]\X
   [6]\IF F[OP]='* THEN RETURN F[LO]*F[RO]\X + F[RO]*F[LO]\X
   [7]\IF F[OP]='/ THEN RETURN %
\   (F[RO]*F[LO]\X - F[LO]*F[RO]\X) / (F[RO]*F[RO])
   [8]\"IMPROPER OPERATOR IN BINARY FORMULA"
   [9]\$
.end

We shall now test ~DERIV~ by using it to find the derivatives
of the formulas ~F~ and ~G~, which have already been constructed.

.examp
\DERIV(F,X)
[LO:1,OP:+,RO:0]
\@F\X
(1+0)
\@G\X
(-((X*(1+0))+((X+3)*1)))
.end

A further simplification of the results (e.g. to collapse
formulas such as 3(1+0)1) could now be performed;
however, we shall not present that here.

.sec(Further Operator Extension,moreopdef)

Given the ability to define new
data types, it is desirable to be able
to redefine common operators to perform
operations on them.
Some general
guidelines should be followed when doing so.

Usually what one wants to do is
to extend an operator to manipulate user-defined
types, yet to have the standard meaning retained
in the case of atomic types.
The required technique in writing a function to
perform this kind of operation is to make
type tests on the operands.  If they do not
match the user-defined types in question, then
the corresponding built-in function should be explicitly
called on the same arguments.

In the following example, we extend the
addition operator to handle instances of type ~<<COMPLEX>~.

.examp
\$<<CADD>(A,B)
   [1]\IF A==COMPLEX THEN %
\   IF B==COMPLEX THEN RETURN %
\\COMPLEX(ADD(A[RP],B[RP]),ADD(A[IP],B[IP])) %
\   ELSE RETURN COMPLEX(ADD(A[RP],B),A[IP])
   [2]\IF B==COMPLEX THEN RETURN COMPLEX(ADD(A,B[RP]),B[IP]) %
\   ELSE RETURN ADD(A,B)
   [3]\$

.apart group
\BINARY("+",CADD)
\X_COMPLEX(8.37, -2.1)
\Y_COMPLEX(-1.1427, 89.54)
\X+Y
[RP:7.2273,IP:87.44]
\X+3
[RP:11.37,IP:-2.1]
\X+Y+1.47
[RP:8.6973,IP:87.44]
\42+7
49
.end
